Title: Building a regression model to predict the Median House Price in Boston¶

  • Group 22: Jamie Jiang, Rico Chan, Nhan Tien Nguyen, Shahrukh Islam Prithibi
  • Word Counts: 1810

Introduction:¶

Background Information:¶

Housing affordability is a topic that draws significant interest from the public worldwide and especially in Vancouver, which is one of the highest cost-of-living cities in Canada. The ability to accurately determine the factors affecting house prices and predict it helps buyers, sellers, and policy makers make informed decisions. A quick search through the scientific literature yields intriguing results. Economic and policy-wise, housing prices are greatly influenced by various factors such as interest/mortgage rates, unemployment rates, inflation rates, and real gross domestic product (1). Furthermore, research conducted by Mi Diao et al also finds human environment and external factors like accessibility to transit and jobs, connectivity, and walkability to be positively associated with residential property values (2). In light of those findings, our project aims to establish a linear model that attempts to predict house prices given a multitude of factors related to urban development and the human environment.

Research Question:¶

  • Can a reduced/selected linear regression model predict better than the full regression model? If yes, which variables can create a better linear regrssion model to predict the median value of owner-occupied homes (MEDV in $1000's)?

  • full model is considered here, since there must be some reasons that the dataset choose these features to study...

  • This question focuses on prediction. With the predictive model, we can not only make predictions but also identify the variables that play a significant role in the variation of house prices.

Data set description:¶

  • The dataset my group will utilize for this project is known as the Boston Housing dataset. is derived from data collected by the U.S. Census Service and is featured in the research paper titled 'Hedonic Housing Prices and the Demand' (3). The research paper explores the relationship between hedonic house prices and the willingness to invest in clean air. Moreover, the finding suggests a modest correlation between house price and the demand for air quality.

  • The dataset contains information related to housing in Boston, Massachusetts and was collected by the US Census Service. The dataset contains 14 variables, including the median value of owner-occupied homes, which we are interested in predicting. The dataset was published in 1978 in a research paper titled “Hedonic Housing Prices and the Demand for Clean Air” in the Journal of Environmental Economics and Management.

`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
  • Here, the noticeable spread hinted at potential outliers, prompting future investigation. Moreover, the high heteroskedasticity seen in the relationship between MEDV and DIS was addressed by exploring a log transformation of the predictor variable.
The EDA involved creating two plots for comparison:¶

Plot A: The original MEDV vs. DIS scatter plot with a straight red regression line.
Plot B: MEDV plotted against the natural logarithm of DIS (ln(DIS)) with a blue regression line.
The visual inspection of Plot B revealed that the blue regression line better captured the changing dynamics of the relationship, unlike the constant slope of the straight red line in Plot A. Specifically, the rate at which MEDV increased with DIS appeared to decrease, indicating diminishing returns. Interpreting the slope coefficient beta in the context of the log-transformed predictor:

  • A 1 log-point increase in weighted distances to the 5 Boston Employment Centers is statistically associated with a beta increase in the Median Value of Owner-Occupied Homes.
  • In simpler terms, a 1% increase in DIS is associated with a (beta / 100) increase in MEDV, providing a more nuanced understanding of the relationship between these variables

Methods and Results¶

  • The steps we used to complete our project include:
  1. Split the data set into three parts: training(35%), validation(35%) and testing set(30%).
  2. Use the training set to run each seletion method: forward selection, lasso, and ridge
  3. Use the training set to construct models based on different methods and use the validation set to test the performance of each model and select a predictive model according to their rmse.
  4. Make prediction: use the test set to show the performance of the selected model.

Step 1: Split the data set into training_Boston_sub(training), selecting_Boston(validation), and testing_Boston (test set)

In [8]:
set.seed(1234)

# Initially, divide the data set -> training(70%) and testing set(30%)
Boston_split <- initial_split(Boston, prop = 0.7, strata = medv)

training_Boston <- training(Boston_split)
testing_Boston <- testing(Boston_split)

# Splitting the training set into two parts, 50% training subset and 50% validation set (for selecting)
training_Boston_sub <- training_Boston %>%
  slice_sample(prop = 0.50)

selecting_Boston <- training_Boston %>%
  anti_join(training_Boston_sub)

Joining with `by = join_by(crim, zn, indus, chas, nox, rm, age, dis, rad, tax,
ptratio, black, lstat, medv)`

  • Then we use house_X_train and house_Y_train for ridge and lasso

Step 4: Predict the response variable(medv) in the test set by using the selected model

In [24]:
# Fit Ridge regression model
reset_house_ridge_model_min_MSE <- glmnet(
  x = house_X_train, 
  y = house_Y_train,
  alpha = 0,  # Setting alpha to 0 for Ridge regression
  lambda = house_lambda_min_MSE_ridge  # Using the lambda that minimizes MSE
)

# Convert the test data into matrix form
boston_X_test <- model.matrix(object = medv ~ ., data = testing_Boston)[, -1]
boston_Y_test <- testing_Boston[, "medv"]

# Make predictions on the test data
house_test_pred_ridge_min <- predict(reset_house_ridge_model_min_MSE, newx = boston_X_test)

#Calculate R-squared manually
r_squared <- 1 - sum((boston_Y_test - house_test_pred_ridge_min)^2) / sum((boston_Y_test - mean(boston_Y_test))^2)

# Calculate RMSE
house_RMSE_result <- tibble(
    Model = "Ridge Regression with minimum cv RMSE",
    RMSE = Metrics::rmse(house_test_pred_ridge_min, boston_Y_test),
    R_squared = r_squared
)

# Display the results

Discussion:¶

Our project sought to answer whether a reduced linear regression model could better predict the median value of Boston homes than the full regression model. In addition, if a reduced model performed better, we wished to investigate the variables that comprised such a model. To achieve this, we split the data into training and testing data. A portion of the training data was also reserved for validation. We trained reduced models using forward selection and LASSO, a model using the Ridge method, and a full model using OLS. By evaluating each model using the validation data, we found that the model from the Ridge method had the best prediction performance with a RMSE of 5.2753, although the reduced model from forward selection performed only marginally worse with a RMSE of 5.2794 (Figure 3.1). To answer our question, we find that the OLS full model does not perform the best. To obtain the final prediction results with our testing data, we used the model from Ridge. The RMSE is 4.7790 (Figure 4.1), which is less than 5.2794, the RMSE we obtained from the validation data. The resulting R-squared is 0.7050 (compared to an R-squared of 0.6801 from the validation data), meaning that 71% of the total variation in median housing prices is explained by the variation in our regressors. Given these results, we can now study and predict the median value housing prices in Boston. This could have an impact in local policymaking, as the insights from this model can be used to identify particular areas in need of affordable housing initiatives. Additionally, this model could be informative for real estate investments since one can roughly assess the median-value housing prices of a Boston neighbourhood by simply using other variables on the area.

There are several limitations to our project. Firstly, due to computational/class/time restrictions, we were unable to assess our models more rigorously using cross-validation. Instead, our approach follows the training, validation, and testing method (essentially 1 fold). This means that the minimum RMSE we obtained using the Ridge method could have been due to chance; another method might have resulted in a lower RMSE had we split the data differently, especially given our small dataset. This could lead to a future question investigating whether we would have still picked the Ridge method for this dataset after using k-fold cross validation. However, implementing forward/backward selection for cross validation would have required map, for loops, or the use of a package not covered in this course. Secondly, our dataset is almost certainly outdated, given that it was originally published in 1978. Changes in economic and social factors, such as inflation, would likely render our model moot in predicting recent housing prices in Boston. A potential area for future research would be to update this dataset and investigate how well our model, trained from 1978 data, predicts today’s housing prices. Furthermore, it could be interesting to train and test a new model using recent data and compare it with our current prediction model.

Lastly, there are several limitations from using the Ridge model, since it shrinks variables toward zero but does not eliminate them entirely. This can potentially increase the risk of overfitting, as the model may learn noise in the data, making it less likely to generalize well to new, unseen data. For instance, during the selection and prediction process, the variables 'tax' and 'black' exhibit very small coefficients in the Ridge model. Moreover, through examining the Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) of each variable in the regression model, 'tax' shows a concerning presence of multicollinearity (VIF = 8.66340). Multicollinearity can make it more challenging for the model to accurately estimate the true relationship between each feature and the response variable. Therefore, for future analysis, we may consider removing the “'tax” feature to evaluate whether there are any improvements in the model's performance. In addition, another drawback of Ridge regression is its sensitivity to the scale of the features. Notably, “'black” and “tax” have values over 100, while the rest are less than 100 or are even less than 10. To further optimize the predictive model, standardizing all features before applying regression models is crucial to ensure that each feature contributes equally to the predictive model.
